			Ché Pasa <span class="c-permalink"><a href="https://www.ianwelsh.net/week-end-wrap-political-economy-november-8-2020/#comment-119434">permalink</a></span>		</div>
		<div class="c-date">
			November 8, 2020		</div>
				<p>Given NL&#8217;s definition of working class, you might be hard put to show that most Trump voters/Republican voters are working class. At least from my perspective, Trump&#8217;s fans and most Rs are petit bourgeois, workers, yes, yet generally independent of an employer but beholden to banks and other lenders, and serving wealth and power to survive.</p>
<p>Most Dems on the other hand are working class, but dominated by those better off at the upper levels &#8212; which usually isn&#8217;t wise. </p>
<p>Independent contractors &#8212; unless at the top of their field &#8212; are often worse off than petit bourgeois, but they&#8217;re awash with freedom, right?</p>
<p>Academics and the professional classes are are even more complicated, usually fitting NL&#8217;s definition of working class, yet believing and acting as if they were anything but. </p>
<p>Both parties represent parts of the upper levels of the working class. Sometimes.</p>
<p>But mostly, both parties represent the interests of wealth and power, usually to the detriment of everyone else.</p>
